Step 3: Train a model using AutoGluon’s Tabular Prediction¶

Requirements:

  • We are prediting count, so it is the label we are setting.
  • Ignore casual and registered columns as they are also not present in the test dataset.
  • Use the root_mean_squared_error as the metric to use for evaluation.
  • Set a time limit of 10 minutes (600 seconds).
  • Use the preset best_quality to focus on creating the best model.
In [13]:
# Set label, ignored columns, metric, time limit, and preset
predictor = TabularPredictor(
    label="count",
    eval_metric="root_mean_squared_error",
    learner_kwargs={"ignored_columns": ["casual", "registered"]},
)

# Fit the model on the training data (train
predictor.fit(train_data=train,
      time_limit=600,# 10 minutes
      presets="best_quality",)

temperature_labels = ['Cold', 'Mild', 'Hot']
train['temp_category'] = pd.cut(train['temp'], bins=temperature_bins, labels=temperature_labels)
test['temp_category'] = pd.cut(test['temp'], bins=temperature_bins, labels=temperature_labels)

# Extract year, month, and day (correction applied)
train["year"] = train["datetime"].dt.year
train["month"] = train["datetime"].dt.month
train["day"] = train["datetime"].dt.day

test["year"] = test["datetime"].dt.year
test["month"] = test["datetime"].dt.month
test["day"] = test["datetime"].dt.day

# Function to define rush hour based on time
def define_rush_hour(hour):
  if 7 <= hour <= 9:
    return "Morning Rush"
  elif 11 <= hour <= 13:
    return "Lunch Rush"
  elif 17 <= hour <= 18:
    return "Evening Rush"
  else:
    return "Non-Rush"

# Extract hour from datetime
train["hour"] = train["datetime"].dt.hour
test["hour"] = test["datetime"].dt.hour

# Apply rush hour function
train["rush_hour"] = train["hour"].apply(define_rush_hour)
test["rush_hour"] = test["hour"].apply(define_rush_hour)

# Categorize temperature (consider adjusting categories based on your data)
temp_categories = pd.cut(train["temp"], bins=[0, 15, 30, 40], labels=["Cold", "Mild", "Hot",])
train["temp_category"] = temp_categories
test["temp_category"] = pd.cut(test["temp"], bins=[0, 15, 30, 40], labels=["Cold", "Mild", "Hot",])

# Categorize wind speed (consider adjusting categories based on your data)
wind_categories = pd.cut(train["windspeed"], bins=[0, 20, 40], labels=["Wind", "Mild Wind",])
train["wind_category"] = wind_categories
test["wind_category"] = pd.cut(test["windspeed"], bins=[0, 20, 40], labels=["Wind", "Mild Wind",])

# Categorize humidity (consider adjusting categories based on your data) - Fixed error
humidity_categories = pd.cut(train["humidity"], bins=[0, 50, 100], labels=["Low Humidity", "High Humidity",])
train["humidity_category"] = humidity_categories
test["humidity_category"] = pd.cut(test["humidity"], bins=[0, 50, 100], labels=["Low Humidity", "High Humidity",])

Make category types for these so models know they are not just numbers¶

  • AutoGluon originally sees these as ints, but in reality they are int representations of a category.
  • Setting the dtype to category will classify these as categories in AutoGluon.
In [50]:

train["weather"] = train["weather"].astype("category")

test["season"] = test["season"].astype("category")

Step 6: Hyper parameter optimization¶

  • There are many options for hyper parameter optimization.
  • Options are to change the AutoGluon higher level parameters or the individual model hyperparameters.
  • The hyperparameters of the models themselves that are in AutoGluon. Those need the hyperparameter and hyperparameter_tune_kwargs arguments.
